The keyboard of the PC on which I solve has been acting up. a new one ha been purche, but isn't set up yet. Some of the key won't trike, or, when tey o, prouce a sssstream of letters. Very frustrating, and, fitting for toay, rather like a game of Whac-a-mmmmole.



whac-an-emmmmmmmu.

@Lewis 
I generally enjoy reading your comments, but I wonder: has there ever been a puzzle you didn't love? 

Not trying to be snarky, just curious.

@Times Rita -- Absolutely, some are sloppy, some are insult-to-the-intelligence easy, some are neverr-should-have-happened inconsistent, etc., and these I generally don't love.

Fortunately, that hardly ever happens with a NYT puzzle, which generally reside on the excellence end of the continuum.

Plus, it helps that I'm generally a glass-half-full sort...

@Motown MD there have been many rebus puzzles where the entries aren’t all the same.

XWordInfo has a page that lists them all.

<a href="https://www.xwordinfo.com/Rebus" target="_blank">https://www.xwordinfo.com/Rebus</a>

@Richard Hawn 

Now that you've looked him up, try to remember him.  He's already appeared five times in the 20s, although the same set of letters has been clued once as a Central Asian savory pastry.  Before 2016, he rarely appeared.

I've never read "The Metamorphosis", but I sure know the name of its main character.

@Al  in Pittsburgh 
Thanks for offering up these three English versions of the first line. I notice that Amazon markets a version (translated by Ian Johnstone) with German on the left-side page and English on the right. What a great idea to aid in appreciation of any translated work. In his translation the first line is:
“One morning, as Gregor Samsa was waking up from anxious dreams, he discovered that in bed he had been changed into a monstrous verminous bug.”

@Delg - I hear you but I think you are clearly mistaken if you believe that "one letter to a square" is an actual rule, much less a basic one. 

Just because the simplest crosswords might seem to adhere to that "rule," doesn't mean that it is a rule at all -- and if so, it is a rule that has been frequently "violated" (you can't really violate something that isn't a rule, right?) for decades now, here and in other venues, in print and online. 

Furthermore, I am quite sure the group of people who enjoy rebuses and other complications far outnumbers the smaller but very whiney group of people who don't.

